TY  - JOUR
AU  - Campbell, John Y.
AU  - Thompson, Samuel B.
T1  - Predicting Excess Stock Returns Out of Sample: Can Anything Beat the Historical Average?
PY  - 2008
Y1  - 2008/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhm055
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 21
IS  - 4
SP  - 1509
EP  - 1531
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Goyal and Welch (2007) argue that the historical average excess stock return forecasts future excess stock returns better than regressions of excess returns on predictor variables. In this article, we show that many predictive regressions beat the historical average return, once weak restrictions are imposed on the signs of coefficients and return forecasts. The out-of-sample explanatory power is small, but nonetheless is economically meaningful for mean-variance investors. Even better results can be obtained by imposing the restrictions of steady-state valuation models, thereby removing the need to estimate the average from a short sample of volatile stock returns.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhm055
ER  - 



